# Canon: the hierarchy of truth

This project has a single canonical chain. All technical artifacts are
derived from the layer above. AI drafts, human approves, approved
content becomes canonical and is referenced thereafter — not re-derived.

```
GDD -> Prototype Scope -> Domain Models -> Tech Designs -> ADRs -> Code
```

- [`design/gdd/`](../../design/gdd) — the Game Design Document. Human-owned.
  Hook-protected. Never edit without the `propose-gdd-edit` skill.
- [`design/scope/`](../../design/scope) — what GDD subsystems this prototype
  implements, at what fidelity. Hook-protected. Modify only through
  `propose-adr` (a scope change is a Tier A decision).
- [`design/domain/`](../../design/domain) — one doc per major domain concept
  (Character, Ability, Combat, Equipment, ...). Plain English + mermaid
  state diagrams + invariants.
- [`design/tech/`](../../design/tech) — one tech design per subsystem;
  derived from its domain doc(s).
- [`design/decisions/`](../../design/decisions) — numbered ADRs recording
  each technical decision with context, alternatives, decision, and
  consequences. Hook-protected.
- [`design/index.md`](../../design/index.md) — master cross-reference.

## Citation rule

Every non-trivial change must cite its governing canonical artifact:

- In the session-brief.
- In the commit message.
- In the plain-English change summary.

If the governing artifact does not exist yet, the change is not ready.
Create the governing artifact first through the appropriate skill.

## Code derives from docs

If code and doc disagree, the doc is authoritative by default. The
resolution is either:

- fix the code to match the doc (most common), or
- update the doc through an ADR recognizing that the doc was wrong.

Do not "fix" the mismatch silently.

## When canon is unclear

If you cannot identify the canonical artifact governing a change, stop
and ask the human. Silent assumption is the exact drift failure mode
the project is defending against.
